Nice! Totally related. We're seeing issues in MS Edge as the problem still exists but the current detection will exclude it from getting the fix. If there was no reason for the restriction I was thinking the check could be reduced to `parent && parent !== parent.top`.

@dmethvin

> To me the ideal resolution here would be for Edge to not throw for this case, or for us to have some way to detect Edge and avoid the cross-iframe access of death

Yap, browsers fixing bugs is ideal. In the meantime however, since cross-frame queries are such a shakey edge case why are you concerned with the possible impact of a vendor-gateless fix? Didn't it worked before the Chrome sandboxed app issue w/o complaint? Or was their an outpouring of perf issues reported because of it? I say let's see if it can be solved in the Chrome app scenario easily and move on. There's no need to try to sniff out IE/Edge for this if it can be solved with a try-catch or something else trivial.

BTW, `try-catch` wouldn't help here as an error is logged but no exception is thrown, i.e. the log:

